: The Case of a Masculine Hero -- tChapter 13. The Temporality and Materiality of Life and Death in a Sepik Village -- tPart IV. Exhibiting Death, Materiality, and Time -- tChapter 14. The Wonderful Exhibition That Almost Was -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWithout exception, all people are faced with the inevitability of death, a stark fact that has immeasurably shaped societies and individual consciousness for the whole of human history. Mirrors of Passing offers a powerful window into this oldest of human preoccupations by investigating the interrelationships of death, materiality, and temporality across far-flung times and places. Stretching as far back as Ancient Egypt and Greece and moving through present-day locales as diverse as Western Europe, Central Asia, and the Arctic, each of the richly illustrated essays collected here draw on a range of disciplinary insights to explore some of the most fundamental, universal questions that confront us.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 04. Okt 2022) 0aDeathvCross-cultural studies. 0aMaterial culture. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Death & Dying.2bisacsh1 aAmmann, Theresa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDitlef Fredriksen, Per, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFalck, Christiane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLehrmann, Malthe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLykkegård, Jeanette, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMartins Lima, Clarissa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMatland, Susan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcLean, Stuart, econtributor.4ctb4https://i